Theme resolution uses a 3-level precedence: (1) .drift/theme.xml — a FULL override with all 18 elements specified as <element id="X" color="Y" bold="true" dim="true"/> entries. If any element is missing, the file is rejected with an error naming the first missing element. This file is committed to git and shared by all developers on the project. (2) .drift/user-settings.xml — per-user preference storing the built-in theme name (e.g. "gruvbox"). This file is NOT committed (listed in .drift/.gitignore). See <ref spec="output_impl.user_settings">user settings</ref>. (3) DefaultTheme — the fallback when neither file exists or specifies a valid theme. If user-settings.xml contains an invalid theme name, drift prints a warning to stderr and falls back to DefaultTheme. See <ref spec="output.theme_system">theme system</ref> and <ref spec="output_impl.theme_loader">theme loader</ref>.